  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Recent Calamities
  author: Seo Geo-jeong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Heavy rains, after all, are bearable—
    the parched earth drinks in their blessing.
    Great drought, after all, is bearable—
    the wetlands receive their gift.
    But fierce winds? These cannot be spoken of.
    All things wither and fade away.
    How can it be that in a single year
    three calamities converge at once?
    Thrice I sigh, and sigh again,
    and so commit this sorrow to verse.
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: The three calamities mentioned are heavy rain, drought, and violent winds—natural disasters that struck the capital during the summer of 1473.
  - key: ''
    value: The poem's structure moves from the tolerable to the intolerable, mirroring how each disaster, while destructive in isolation, becomes overwhelming when combined.
